post_text:
All employees, students and visitors will be responsible for self-screening before attending school each day. We have a tool that will make this process easy for you and we are requesting that you use the tool. This will allow us to keep screening documentation.

Student Screening - A family downloads the app and creates a parent account. The parent adds in their student's information as a "dependent" in the app. Before dropping a student off or putting a student on the bus, the parent is able to check in student on app and certify they are symptom-free and do not have a history of exposure. Families do not have a phone? We can send out a unique link to allow families to check in students on a computer or any device without downloading the app.

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

An estimated 5% of kids under the age of 5 weren‚Äôt counted in the 2010 Census. That‚Äôs about 1 million young children, the highest of any group. We need your help closing this gap.

Let‚Äôs use this set back as a set up for the next 10 years, to fund programs such as Food Stamps (Supplemental Nutritional Assistance Program or SNAP), the National School Lunch Program, and the Children‚Äôs Health Insurance Program (CHIP).

As of 05/09/20, Lipscomb County 2020 Census Response: 26.3%, Follett 20.0%, Darrouzett 21.1%, Booker 33.0%, and Higgins 14.0%.

post_text:
Panthers & Lady Panthers,

This current pandemic has hearts aching in so many communities. I am sure you have all read the executive order derived from Governor Abbott that will close our schools until May 4th. We are experiencing an unparalleled time where school, businesses, and social interactions are so greatly impacted and considered a luxury. We understand how this impacts you all, especially our seniors and athletes.

Coach Copley reached out expressing the need and desire to spread optimism through Dumas ISD‚Äôs challenge of all Texas High Schools in spreading hope.

As a program and school district, we will shine our stadium lights from 8pm-9pm nightly in a show of optimism and unity. We have accepted Dumas ISD‚Äôs challenge of all Texas high schools to join them in doing so. We can‚Äôt meet up there as a group, but our amazing coaches will be around the stadium and look forward to the shine of our lights. Our future is bright and together we will get through this ordeal. Love your family and continue to work and continue to be great servant leaders. We love you all.
text:
Panthers & Lady Panthers,

We understand how this impacts you all, especially our seniors and athletes.

Coach Copley reached out expressing the need and desire to spread optimism through Dumas ISD‚Äôs challenge of all Texas High Schools in spreading hope.

As a program and school district, we will shine our stadium lights from 8pm-9pm nightly in a show of optimism and unity. We have accepted Dumas ISD‚Äôs challenge of all Texas high schools to join them in doing so. We can‚Äôt meet up there as a group, but our amazing coaches will be around the stadium and look forward to the shine of our lights. Our future is bright and together we will get through this ordeal. Love your family and continue to work and continue to be great servant leaders. We love you all.

post_text:
Notice to Parents: Head Lice
Unfortunately, it is that time of year where we see a spread of lice due to the garments being worn and hung near others. Your child may have been exposed to head lice. Please examine your child‚Äôs hair and scalp for evidence of live lice, lice eggs, or nits (egg casings left behind after lice have hatched). If lice or eggs are present, they will be found close to the scalp. If you find head lice please notify your child‚Äôs school, daycare or others with whom your child may have had direct head to head contact. Children with head lice should be treated as soon as possible to
minimize the spread to other individuals.
School policy excludes students from school with live lice.

This article provides great information how how to help contain and get rid of lice.
https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/treatment-tests-and-therapies/no-panic-guide-to-head-lice-treatment

***PSA***
We are currently living in a social media era. Research says that our children today are the most connected generation there has ever been, however, they are the loneliest. The constant interaction with screens and apps that are developed to aim at anonymity can be linked to cyber bullying and greatly affects our students, today. Please be aware of what your children have on their phones. It is a lot of responsibility at their fingertips.

https://www.internetmatters.org/hub/guidance/parents-guide-what-is-yolo-app-and-is-it-safe/

post_text:
Our recent Scholastic Book Fair was another huge success! We surpassed our $1800 goal by over $700! Follett ISD is one of the top box fairs in Scholastic! The credit for this success is community support, an incredible Scholastic rep, a dedicated group of Book Fair volunteers, and parents/teachers/administration and students who love to read.
Teachers put 38 new books in their classroom, Book Fair volunteers picked 33 books for their hard work, 8 students won the Book Fair coloring contest and carried off the book of their choice, 14 students won the book of their choice in the drawing in the ‚ÄúI wish I could win...‚Äù contest, 28 students were visited by the Book Fair Fairy, and last but not least, 85 books will be added to the Follett ISD Library. THANK YOU!

Trisha Nelson and her son Chase are still in the hospital recovering from their injuries. The oldest Tristin and their 5 year old Kyndall suffered some bruises and concussion but are doing well.

Hey Panthers! Your elementary children were sent home with a great opportunity for Summer Reading. These Build Your Own Book Boxes will not only benefit your children but our amazing library! For just $35 your child will bring home 4 books AND will help our library obtain $17 in books to add to our collection for next year.

We also have 19 students looking for sponsors. If you are able to sponsor a child, please contact our Educational Services Representative, Cat Davis or send a check or cash to the office for her to pick up.

The order forms are due Friday, May 17 in the morning so we can get the books in before we get out for summer. Have a great weekend!
